[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering language integration**\n\nI'm thinking about integrating Java and Scala in my project. My test class prefers Scala, but I wonder if I can add a Java file instead. The Gradle Scala plugin compiles Java from specific directories, and placing Java in `src/test/scala` could be tricky since it won't compile properly. I’ll need to keep tests in Scala within the designated folder. I have to ensure that the Java helper can effectively interact with Scala while implementing logging functionalities without facing any access restrictions.\n\n**Evaluating the API and dependencies**\n\nI’m assessing whether the current artifact API is functional enough for my needs. The public API isn't directly accessible to Scala users, but it is available through Java bytecode, covering methods in the source. I'll need to edit the `build.gradle` to include `testImplementation pekko-actor_3:$libraryVersion`, possibly also adding `scala-library`. However, I want to be cautious about the user context and only edit files that are allowed, which complicates modifying this for Java helper classes.\n\n**Exploring Scala class options**\n\nI'm considering creating a Scala class that utilizes `scala.annotation.nowarn` and `import scala.language.dynamics`, but access may still be restricted. Using `erasedValue` isn’t an option either. I wonder if I could directly invoke static methods with backticked mangled names, like `org.apache.pekko.macros.LogHelper.isDebugEnabled$(...)`. However, I’m questioning whether access to the object, class, or trait marked as `private[pekko]` will even be possible. There’s definitely some uncertainty here!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_099444905eef4ef20169fc381211848190be983351b12cba83\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp_Dgbv05BYOYjR3Qb5cGgkM5EYYSGyBi33YwY7Q3mjWJ4g--k4jtKzotd47nYvzujlNDah8pQSoLnbBuvIHu-DMM9KHqOxbuGLtnEvUsBYou